headline: US Bancorp quarterly profit beats estimates as bad loan provisions shrink
summary: The Minnesota-based bank's provisions for credit losses declined 12% to $501 million in the quarter, driven by improved credit quality and loan portfolio sales, beating analysts' average expectation of $610.3 million in bad loan provisions, according to estimates compiled by LSEG. The sale of certain loans in the quarter resulted in a $53 million reserve release. Credit quality remained stable to improving, despite ongoing economic uncertainty, the bank said.
